Photos



I like that a bicycle not only gives you traveling freedom in San Francisco, but also /time freedom/ you don't have to worry about the time  (except for sundown for me!) since you can be anywhere you want at any time.





Bonus: Health benefits

I've been riding bicycles for about 8 months now and have lost 10 pounds doing nothing other than just riding bicycles to work. I eat more now because I weigh less. I like eating. Also, I drink WAY more water than I used to do so. There is nothing better than being really thirsty and drinking clean water! I don't really know the health benefits of riding bicycles daily because my goal was to save money (remember that MUNI ticket? Yea...).





I really don't like the gym. I like experiences, so I take any chance I get to go on a bicycle or on a hike. Blake Lively





Securing your bike



When I was a kid I used to pray every night for a new bicycle. Then I realised that the Lord doesn't work that way so I stole one and asked Him to forgive me. Emo Philips



The second biggest downside to bicycling is theft. There is nothing worse than your ride home getting stolen. Stealing bikes is easier than stealing a car. A car can be tracked down if not taken apart, it's much more visible. A bike is much lighter, smaller, and easier to take apart. Bikes get stolen and that is part of life, but there is a bright light at the end of the tunnel. Most workplaces now have caged bicycle rooms. There are more cameras on the streets to deter thieves. Even technology lets you track your bike if it's moved or act like a skunk by making it smell really bad if someone cuts your lock. Most of these new technologies cost a lot of money though, sometimes as much as a cheap bike. Here are some tips on securing your bike on a budget:



1) Ask your workplace if you are allowed to bring your bicycle in. Be respectful, bike tires are like markers, they will mark walls.

2) Use a quality U-Lock. When locking your bicycle, use the "triangle", Google Bicycle triangle lock and look at the images to get an idea of what it is.

3) Don't use a bike that you absolutely love, use a 'beater' bike. You can also make your bike look like crap by intelligently putting mud and fake rust in places that doesn't affect moving parts.

4) Lock your bicycle where there is a lot of traffic. Lock your bikes where other bikes are locked. If there is an easier looking target, your bike might be ignored.



Buying a bicycle



You can't buy happiness, but you can buy a bicycle and that's pretty close. -Anonymous



Buying a bicycle can be overwhelming, there is just so much stuff out there that it can get confusing. I recommend gathering some money you can "throw away", around $100. Then go on Craigslist and see anything that looks good (this is a large topic on its own since there are many "Walmart" brands, and a few quality brands of bicycles. Go visit the bicycle and move the parts, any squeaking can be a sign of a badly maintained bike. If it was stored for a long time, there might be rust on it that you want to clean. If the frame of the bicycle has rust it is generally not a great bicycle. Most bicycle are made of steel or aluminum. A quality steel bicycle is heavier, but can last forever because steel is workable. Aluminum is lighter and more common, but once it cracks, that's it for the bicycle. Generally, avoid carbon fiber bicycles, they are probably the worse for beginners as if you tighten a screw on it too hard, it will crack it, making it useless. Most light aluminum bicycles weight about 1 to 2 pounds more than a carbon fiber bicycle, so really, it's not worth it.



Before buying a used bicycle, ask if you can get the serial number of the bicycle to run online to see if it's stolen or not. Do not buy a stolen bicycle, you are only helping the stolen bicycle market. All bicycles come with a serial number, even my cheapo Vilano bicycle. If it's not stolen, check if the serial number was registered so you can transfer it to your name, if not, register it once you bought it. There are many "databases" online that can act as an authority on what serial number belongs to who. None of these are official government agencies though. They do help law enforcement though for when they find your bicycle, it helps them get it back to you.



In terms of the right size bicycle, check Google for "bicycle frame sizing" and find your "bicycle" size, if you are in between two numbers , go with the smaller one. A smaller bicycle is easier to adjust to your size than a larger one is. A bicycle is very adjustable so don't worry if it's exactly your size, just as long as it's around your size or a little smaller.



Most parts can be interchanged on a bicycle unless you got a specialty bicycle (like my Schwinn Loop), so I recommend focusing on the frame of the bicycle. Once you are done with the checking the frame for cracks, corrosion, and bends, you can move on to removable parts like rims, tires, chain, pedals, handlebars, shifters, brakes, etc. All these parts are interchangeable and there are very common standards that help with compatibility. The parts that can be adjusted are the seat, brakes, gear shifters, and tires. If any of these aren't immediately working properly, it's not a complete deal breaker, you can adjust or readjust these with a few simple tools (most of the time just a 5mm allen wrench and a Philips screwdriver).



